05788nam a22009615i 9780674593831DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20131973mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1024017142  a(OCoLC)1029820011  a(OCoLC)1032685785  a(OCoLC)1037979302  a(OCoLC)1041985239  a(OCoLC)1046609921  a(OCoLC)1047010501  a(OCoLC)1049630248  a(OCoLC)1054876057  a97806745938317 a10.4159/97806745938312doi  a(DE-B1597)251894  a(OCoLC)979954084  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aBUS0690002bisacsh1 aWilkenfeld, Harold C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTaxes and People in Israel /cHarold C. Wilkenfeld.  aReprint 2014 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4c©1973  a1 online resource (307 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHarvard Law School International Tax Program ;v300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction: The Administrative Crisis -- t2. The Tax System of Israel -- t3. Development of the Administrative Structure -- t4. External Relations -- t5. Men and Machines -- t6. Improvement of Income Tax Assessment Techniques -- t7. Administrative and Judicial Resolution of Disputed Determinations -- t8. Overcoming Tax Evasion -- t9. Administration of Taxes on Property -- t10. Compulsory Payments -- tBibliography Index -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"In tax administration," writes the author, "all countries can learn from each other." This revealing case study of the development of Israel's tax system--a system which has dealt with the full panoply of problems that tax administrators must face and which is further characterized by heavy taxation--offers a wealth of noteworthy examples for other countries. Harold C. Wilkenfeld presents a detailed account of the historical and economic realities that forged Israel's elaborate tax structure from the Ottoman period to the present day. He scrutinizes such areas as the crises that Israel's tax administration faced shortly after the State achieved its independence, the problems which had to be solved, the formulation of administrative policy, the interplay of a developing civil service and a developing citizenry. All of these areas are viewed in the context of an evolving economy and a continuing external conflict. The author presents practical guidelines for countries interested in advancing the effectiveness of tax administration. For instance, many of the Israeli administration's tactics against tax evasion may be transplantable to other nations. Likewise, a number of the technical solutions to administrative problems of both direct and indirect taxes can certainly and readily be adapted to conditions in a number of developing countries. Taxes and People in Israel comes as a welcome addition to a field which offers few critical, historical studies of the entire tax system of a country. It will be of considerable interest to tax administrators and ought to be read by every new head of a tax administration. It should also prove a valuable source to public administrators, lawyers, sociologists, economists, and anyone concerned with giving fiscal advice to the developing countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aSteuersystem. 0aTax administration and procedure. 0aTaxation. 0aÖffentliche Verwaltung. 4aLAW / General. 4aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General. 4aTax administration and procedure -- Israel -- History. 4aTaxation -- Israel -- History. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh1 aOldman, Oliver, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Co